    <!-- Section 29: Lesson - General Cleaning Techniques -->
    <div id="section29" class="section hidden">
        <h2>Lesson: General Cleaning Techniques</h2>
        <p>Let’s dive into the second part of the Post-Construction Cleaning Course! Below, I’ve structured the content into clear lessons and questions, mirroring the engaging and digestible format of the first part. Each section uses bullet points, icons, and well-spaced text for readability. Let’s get started.</p>
        <p>Here’s how to clean efficiently after construction:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><i class="fas fa-broom"></i> Start with "dry before wet": Begin by removing loose dirt and debris using dry methods like sweeping, vacuuming, or dusting. Only then move to wet cleaning (e.g., mopping or wiping) to avoid turning dust into muddy streaks.</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i> Work from top to bottom: Clean high areas first—ceilings, light fixtures, and shelves—then progress downward to walls, furniture, and floors. This prevents falling dust from dirtying already-cleaned areas.</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-map"></i> Clean room by room systematically: Tackle one room at a time, starting from the farthest corner and moving toward the exit. This keeps you organized and avoids tracking dirt into finished spaces.</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-th"></i> Break it down into sections: Divide large surfaces (like floors or walls) into manageable chunks. Focus on one section at a time for thorough cleaning without feeling overwhelmed.</li>
        </ul>
        <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
        <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 30: Lesson - Surface-Specific Techniques -->
    <div id="section30" class="section hidden">
        <h2>Lesson: Surface-Specific Techniques</h2>
        <p>Different surfaces need tailored approaches:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><i class="fas fa-toolbox"></i> Match your method to the material:
                <ul>
                    <li>Hard floors (tile, wood, laminate): Sweep or vacuum, then mop with a cleaner suited to the surface (e.g., pH-neutral for wood).</li>
                    <li>Carpets: Vacuum deeply with a powerful machine, then steam clean for stains.</li>
                    <li>Glass/windows: Dust frames first, then use glass cleaner with a lint-free cloth.</li>
                    <li>Metal fixtures: Wipe with a damp cloth and polish if needed.</li>
                    <li>Tile grout: Scrub with a grout brush and a mild cleaner or baking soda paste.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-spray-can"></i> Choose the right cleaning agent: Use appropriate cleaners to avoid damage:
                <ul>
                    <li>Glass cleaner for windows/mirrors.</li>
                    <li>Wood polish for wooden surfaces (test first).</li>
                    <li>Degreaser for greasy areas like kitchens.</li>
                    <li>Disinfectant for bathrooms.</li>
                    <li>All-purpose cleaner for general surfaces.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-tint"></i> Don’t over-wet surfaces: Excess water can harm wood or drywall. Use a damp (not dripping) cloth or mop and dry immediately if necessary.</li>
        </ul>
        <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
        <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
    </div>

